Anarotali is a city as remote as an abandoned city; it includes a one-and-a-half-hour flight from Jayapur, the provincial administrative center, to Nabeer, and a five-hour shake in a hired car.
There's no public transport here.
The city, with a population of about 19,000, is made up of wooden houses with bamboo fences; the roofs of corrugated steel are painted with rust in a wide range of red colors.
Not many of the Indonesians, let alone the journalists, and almost none of the foreigners, have come here.
Prior to the arrival of Christian missionaries, the pope was worshipping a god called Uga Tameo.
There have been other changes.
“We were unfavorable to wear this dress,” Deguei says, pointing to his bright, hand-wrapped turban, a dark skirt, and a bright shirt.
"We used to wear only leaves on the body."
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, 28 per cent of its population live below the poverty line, and child mortality and literacy are among the worst in Asia.
But it's also Indonesian gold land.
The world's largest and most lucrative gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Freeport McMoran, is only 60 miles from Pania, a high-rise province about the size of New Jersey, where 153,000 people live.
In 2015 alone, Freeport produced about $3.1 billion in gold and copper.
In addition, Papua can show up on forest reserves, which are estimated at $78 billion.
This wealth, however, brings with it one misfortune for the Papuas, guaranteeing that the strong Indonesian armed forces maintain their suffocating presence here.
According to an investigation into The New York Times in 2005, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid nearly $20 million to local troops and units, up to $150,000 to one officer.
The demands for greater autonomy on the part of the pope threaten the existence of this golden vein and are ruthlessly suppressed.
According to human rights defenders, more than 500,000 Papuas have been killed by the Indonesian military since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and deprived of their liberty.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, the massacres in the native highlands of Papua in the 1970s can be considered as genocide.
Last year alone, the Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
“We will lose everything,” a report published in 2016 by the Brisbane Diocese contains evidence of the atrocities committed in the previous year, such as summary executions, torture – especially, as another report states, rape and electrocution – and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
“It's hard to count the number of casualties, because the incidents occur every week,” says Andreas Harmono, a researcher in Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
The hays have been protracted, as Papua ' s resources have attracted the inflow of resettlers from other parts of Indonesia.
The 3.5-million population of the province is 83 per cent Christian, but the demographics change as Muslim economic migrants come from densely populated Indonesian islands – Java, Sumatra, and Sulawesi.
Yavan shops, “warungi”, sell fried chickens and a blend of gado-gado vegetables served with peanut sauce.
