“This is why the natives of Papua, Mother (female) of Papua, have lost their marketplace.”
Indonesian President Joko Vidodo, known as the Jokowi, vowed to address the inequalities and violations of rights in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the President's Palace in Jakarta, a former carpenter enlisted the support of 27 of Papua's 29 districts, including the Paniai.
But there has been little change in Papua, and the locals feel loyal.
“Our hearts are broken, because in 2014 we voted for Jokowi, waiting for him to live up to our hopes for justice,” Yoo says.
In fact, just two months after the October inauguration, Jokowi Paniai survived a tragedy.
On 7 December 2014, a group of 11 children was on the street singing Christmas anthems at a fire in Enarotali, when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle broke out of the dark.
Scared kids told them to turn on the headlights.
According to local pastor Javedt Tebai, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and, after a while, returned with four soldiers.
According to the victims and eyewitnesses, the soldiers who were drunk chased the children and beat them with rifles.
Then one of the soldiers shot at a group of children.
One child, Julianus Emo 16, was so badly beaten, he fell into a coma.
A couple of hours later, someone set fire to a government office nearby, and the next day, the situation got worse.
Around a thousand pope men, women and children gathered in a football field in front of the local police station and the military command center to demand justice.
They brought their ritual hunter bows and performed the white, the popuas pago dance, running in circles and playing the bird's singing.
Some protesters began to throw rocks at the police station and the military base.
When the situation got hot, the internal radios were ordered to “if the mob resists more than three times, shoot them,” it sounded like an official document that was seen by Time magazine reporters, but was not published in the local media.
The 50 - year - old Jeremias Cayama, head of the Kogo Koto district in Enarotali, felt the danger and called for calm, asking the crowd to go home.
No one wanted to listen to it.
"When I turned, my left wrist was suddenly hit by a bullet," he told the magazine "TIME", standing on the porch of his brightly dyed wooden house.
Kaime still doesn't know who shot him, but he says the bullet came from the shreening of the soldiers gathered.
"There was a mob, there was a lot of shots," he adds.
The local Alfius Jowa was shot three times, as his cousin, who was a witness to the shooting, said.
“I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him,” Johns, who, like many Indonesians, used one name.
"I saw him dead... I kissed him."
General Jotge Mende, Chief Inspector of the Papua Police, told reporters that his officers were just "protecting" their base because it was under attack.
“We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us,” said the Papua Police Commissioner Pujo Sulistio in 2015.
“This is a matter of life and death.”
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed, and much more wounded.
The news of the murders only got to Jakarta the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi spoke in Jayapur, expressing sympathies to the families of the victims and vowing to address the historical abuse of power in Papua.
“I want this situation to be resolved immediately, that it will never recur in the future,” he said.
In October 2016, the Minister for Security, Viranto, said that he would set up a non-judicial organization to put an end to historical human rights violations.
But almost immediately, the excuses went.
“Most of the violations have occurred a long time ago.
Some of them occurred in the nineties or at the start of the zeros.
The fact is, we certainly want to deal with these violations, but there are procedures to go through," he said.
Viranto then gave up on his word with the magazine TIME on June 5, in Jakarta, and said he was not planning to set up an organization to deal with complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, "Everything will be decided by a court of law."
Viranto, who was accused of “offences against humanity” in connection with the death of more than 1,000 people during the 1999 blood-blooded East Timor independence vote, said that 11 human rights violations in Papua had already been resolved, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the Paniai victims met such statements with a gloomy distrust.
“In the last three years, I have been interrogated four times, but there has been no change at all,” says Johannes.
"I'm tired."
He says years later, he still lives in fear.
"I'm scared," he says.
"I'm afraid I'm gonna be arrested by the military, I'm afraid I'm gonna get shot."
His brother Jacobus was also of the view that the people of Pania were afraid to talk about the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after he helped bury four of the victims.
"After we buried the bodies, the military came after me," he says.
The shooting didn't stop.
On Tuesday, the Indonesian police shot at the villagers in the nearby Pania district of Deiya.
