The Deyai Parliament demanded that the officers involved in the incident be called to account, and the mobile police brigade was withdrawn from the region.
Paniai has always been a sick place for the Indonesian government.
Lack of meaningful development is a source of dissatisfaction among the tribes of the Meo, the Moni, the Dani, and the Damals, all over the green central highlands of Papua.
Many have joined the Free Papua Movement (OPM), an insurgency army that claims to defend the rights of the popuas by launching sporadic attacks and raids on Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the top OPM leaders come from Pania, including Thadius Yogi and Daniel Judas Komia.
As a response, in recent years thousands of people have been arrested in Paniai and have been arbitrarily detained by the military under the guise of “Protection of national independence”.
Some never came back.
In Papua, Paniai is considered to be “a sad, forgotten place”.
Poverty exacerbates discontent.
A small quantity of rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for the locals.
The bread is, to the same extent, unavailable.
People here grow everything they eat, mostly a note, as well as some fruit and leafy vegetables.
Agriculture is the work of women, each of whom can care for four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually keep most of the harvest for the family, and the rest is sold on the local market.
The ten tubers are worth just 10,000 rupees (75 cents).
Over time, there has been an increase in the economic disparity between indigenous Papuas and new migrants, who have come in large numbers since the introduction of new flights to Nabir airport.
Few existing vacancies are usually available to better-educated and affluent migrants.
The popes rarely have the money or the skills to run their own competitive business.
