Isolation keeps Papua far from the rest of the world.
In addition, restrictions on the work of the international media continue to be severe.
Earlier this year, French journalists Frank Escudie and Basil Lonshan were deported from Papua for “inconclusively aligned with the relevant organizations” despite having been given rare permissions to do videos.
According to Felim Keene, the Deputy Director for Asia, Human Rights Watch, the promises made during the Jokowi campaign to lift media restrictions in order to promote transparency and development have not been met.
“At present, foreign journalists trying to report from the rebel eastern Indonesian provinces, Papua and West Papua face new dangers: denial of a visa and blacklisting,” he said in a statement.
Lack of press attention means that international pressure on the Government of Indonesia is largely restricted to Papua ' s immediate neighbours.
In March, six Pacific States – Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, Marshall Islands, and Solomon Islands – requested the UN Human Rights Council to investigate “diverse and widespread violations” in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
The same countries have backed OPM in the past.
A representative of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Indonesia, Arramanat Nasir, reneged on the group's statement, telling journalists in Jakarta that “In Indonesia, there is still a democratic system and a free press, so it would be difficult to cover up evidence of human rights violations”.
Locals want more foreign governments to focus on the situation.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by the Netherlands Human Rights Ambassador, Kiis Van Bahar, visited Jayapur on 4 May, the local people broke the silence, saying, "We want freedom," as the source, who also attended the meeting but wanted to stay anonymous.
In Indonesia, new presidential elections will take place in 2019, but the popes say they're unlikely to vote for Jokowi again.
