Judges are offered protection from the Presidents
The Presidential Council for Human Rights (CHR) on behalf of Vladimir Putin has put forward proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The HRC proposes to limit the powers of the Presidents of the Courts and to introduce their electiveness.
For the Courts of Appeal and Cassation, the HRC wishes to introduce special districts that will not be linked to the administrative and territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court should also submit its proposals in the context of the presidential mandate.
The HRC has completed the development of proposals that will strengthen the independence of Russian justice.
This work was carried out by HRC on behalf of Wladimir Putin on 3 January 2017, which was given by the President after a meeting with the Council.
The meeting with the Council on 8 December 2016 included individual cases of judicial arbitrariness, as well as problems of public control in places of detention (see OS, 9 December).
The work of the HRC has resulted in 25 proposals, which address both the issues of ensuring the independence of the judiciary and the identification of miscarriage of justice, as well as the financing of the courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of Cremlin human rights defenders was to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts in order to increase the independence of the rest of the judiciary.
If the candidate for the position of judge has been successful and has received the support of the judicial community, the President of the Court, according to the HRW, must submit him for appointment without the right to refuse, as the law now permits.
It is also proposed to disqualify the President from assigning cases to the judges.
Doing this, the experts say, can be a specially written computer program.
The HRC also considers that the President is not entitled to “predetermine the results of a judge's qualification, initiate disciplinary action, and make decisions on the establishment of additional material payments”.
At the same time, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to move to “elect the presidents of the courts themselves” and to “entitle them to a relatively short period of office with a mandatory rotation”.
The President of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation now appoints all the Presidents of the Courts (representing the Republican to the Regional Courts) for a period of six years.
In order to protect the judges from the pressure of regional administrations, the HRC proposes to re-organize the appeal and cassation before the courts of general jurisdiction.
Their structure is now linked to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The HRC states that “it is necessary to ensure that individual courts of appeal and cassation are organized not at the level of the regional courts in the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, but in the judicial districts”.
The experts base their practice on the practice of arbitral tribunals.
There are “judiciary districts” which do not match administrative division in the Russian Federation, but which thus guarantee greater independence from regional officials, who find it difficult to use “telephone law”.
The HRC ' s peace judges propose to be strengthened by the people ' s jurors in order to deal with some of the “civil and administrative categories” with them.
For example, the deprivation of parental rights, reinstatement at work, the protection of honour and dignity, the denial of driver's license, etc.
"These are just our proposals," explained the "OJ" member of the HRC, a retired judge of the Constitutional Court of Tamara Morsjakov.
She also recalled that the President ' s mandate concerned not only the HRC, but also the Supreme Court, which had not yet made its proposals public.
There is still time to carry out the task of the Supreme Court (with the Office of the Attorney-General and the Commissioner for Human Rights in the Russian Federation).
To inform Vladimir Poetin of the effectiveness of the Russian Federation ' s independence of justice, the President of the Armed Forces, Vyacheslav Lebedev, is due to do so by 1 September.
Living a high life: half-storys and clever designs have turned this little place in Earls Court into a spacious place.
Joan Lee, a former banker interested in real-estate repairs, moved from a spacious house in Knightsbridge to an apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the ground floor of a pretty model home like Queen Anne, and in favor of a new design, it says that Joan didn't pack her stuff and move again.
"I used to live with my ex-boyfriend in Knightsbridge in a much larger area," Joan tells me.
"I was looking for something comparable for my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earls Court, and there were also high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered her a price on the same day."
Since the first view, an apartment of 1,000 square feet has been refurbished.
Originally, it was an apartment with one bedroom of complex design – to get to the bedroom, to go through the kitchen – and Joanna wanted to add space to store things and half-decks to get the best out of the rich height of the ceilings.
"I wanted high ceilings, big windows, a lot of light.
That was my demand," she says.
To this end, she hired Erfan Azadi from Notting Hill's "Duck & Shed", an architectural design studio, to use the ceilings 12.5 feet high and to build a home that would not only be a successful project, but would be right for Joan to live.
The ceiling was not high enough to set up two spaces over one another, so the architectural task was to create a semi-deck where you could stand up in full size.
Erfan had to think creatively to deal with the breeze.
“Working with steel designs is very complex,” he explains.
“We needed to place the space so that it would be one over the other, and we didn't have to bend.
It was not just to build a simple platform, but to bend the design so that it would be at the right height and make it possible to use the spaces from the top and bottom.
This decision enabled Erfan to set up two full-sized rooms one over the other in the space, and a lot more interesting.
From the semi-deck through the vintage copper light window, "Retrouvius" opens a view of the luxurious living room below.
Mirror furniture with golden trim, silver accents, and vintage light from Serge Muy set the design style.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding sight, space, and light.
The short hallway is framed with mirrors to make it look longer.
In the kitchen, a mirror ward looks like a window to the other room.
At the inlet, the mirror cupboards are used to store all of Joan’s dishes.
To create a sense of more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can block the kitchen when it is not used.
There's nothing new to the cuisines.
The unique thing about this kitchen is, it's a moving door up, like in the garage.
“The engineering was involved here,” Erfan tells us about the wooden fibrous shield door.
“It is equipped with a counterweight, so when you push a door up, it slips very easily.”
Thanks to the wise use of space and storage space, Joan received an additional 16 square meters, an extra bedroom, and an improved plan.
“In the end, the area of the floors is exactly what you're going to sell, that is, what your property is worth,” Erfan says.
“Surely, a real-estate agent will go in and make calculations based on the gender area.”
Here, they have been able to expand the area of the floors by using quality materials that give space a shade of luxuriousness.
“Materials are what we touch, so they help to make an emotional connection to the home,” Erfan says.
“No one falls in love with electrical wiring in the walls.
It's important, but it doesn't touch the strings of our hearts."
This is an indication that, with good design and an extra metre, an apartment can turn out to be something that's amazing.
In fact, like Joan, you can decide to stay.
