Brothers are fighting for a real-estate empire worth over $500 million.
Two brothers are fighting for one of Victoria's largest real-estate empires worth over $500 million – 40 years after their Italian ancestors founded the dynasty.
The former director of Carlton Football Club and the developer Colin de Lutis live at the Torak Palace at three doors from his younger brother Paul, who sued the Supreme Court for a division of property and assets.
Paul wants to leave the family business since 2014, but the Supreme Court is still in a bitter dispute about the terms of the divorce.
The brothers, together with their mother, Anne, own 87 sites worth over half a billion dollars, which have been bought since their family bought a shop on Smith Street in Collingwood in 1973.
There the family founded Westco Jeans, which grew up in a network of 160 outlets.
It was sold in 1999 for $85 million.
The money was invested in real estate, and the De Lutis family's property list today includes office buildings, construction sites in Brunswick and Sorrento, apartments on the Golden Bank and Mount Bueller, and shopping centres in the suburbs.
By agreement with the late father, Colin - who Paul describes as the "primary driving force and dominant person" of the De Lutis family - owns about two thirds of the company's assets, and Paul owns about one third.
According to the court, this means that Colin's property is 316 million and Paul's property is 176 million.
The division of property and money has become a stumbling block for Paul.
"The section proposed by Colin gives him, in my view, the best parts of property," he wrote in his first statement in 2015.
Last Friday, after a number of failed attempts at reconciliation, the first Supreme Court hearing took place.
The brothers are now arguing about who will control the existing business - from which Paul thought Colin had expelled him.
Colin claims it's not, but he's blaming Paul for incompetent management of some of the facilities.
In Colin's statement at the start of the trial, he said he was looking forward to a settlement.
"My Italian roots make me think of the family as the top priority," he wrote.
The court's costs are rising like a snowball: hundreds of pages of testimony, e-mails and reports from companies such as Deloitte, Pitcher Partners, and Charter Keck Cramer; both parties have brought in the best-known lawyers, including royal attorney Allan Myers, and the best cooks.
Mrs. De Lutis and her late wife, Luigi, were immigrants from Italy; since the late 1950s, they have run dairy bars and malls, and in the early 1970s they bought a shop in Brunswick.
Under financial guarantees, they bought a shop in Collingwood, where Colin opened the first family jeans shop.
Colin says he ran Westco when he was "in the last grade of the school, and Paul was a boy (about 10 years old)."
Anna De Lutis says that he and Luigi, who died in 2012, were hoping to hand over their property to their sons without conflict.
"Louisi used to tell me he didn't want the brothers to go to court," she wrote.
The other two brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer part of the De Lucis group; Colin says Mark got 10 million when he left the business, and Luke 26 million.
According to Paul, both Luke and Mark were "dissatisfied with the financial terms of their office."
Colin was not a public figure, even though he was a former member of the AFL Club's board of directors and, according to a 2015 biography by Eddie McGuire, the best friend of a TV star.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul and their lawyers on Friday.
Only Colin replied with a text message that, since the case had not yet been heard in court, "I really have nothing to say."
"I'm very, very sorry that my brother Paul has decided to sue me and lament the name of our family in court," he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin testified that he was trying to meet his brother's demands.
"Our father wouldn't want to see Paul and me arguing in court," he said, adding, "still hope for a solution to the conflict."
This hope must have dissipated on Friday.
"The decision in our case will be made soon by the court," writes Colin.
