Our work has not been limited to the release of seamen from the Chebotarev Mechanical.
We have been able to reach out to the representatives of all major groups opposing each other in the Libyan conflict, as well as to Tripoli (where the UN-recognized government is based under Faiz Saraj. - "Oz") and to Tobrook (the parliamentary section that opposes the Government and supports marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls the eastern part of Libya. - "Oz").
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (the Libyan Vice-Prime Minister) we have been able to quickly agree on the release of Russian seamen.
It was then decided to make better use of those contacts, to set up a contact group.
Its task is to analyse the situation, to identify key factors and players, and to engage with all parties to the conflict.
I want to stress, in particular, that in Libya we do not want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict; we are engaged in a dialogue with all.
How many people are in the contact group, and how many of them are in Libya on a permanent basis?
The contact group now has five members.
Among them are people with experience in the security forces, including the Ministry of Defence.
We also want to include in the group of regional experts from the Institute of the Middle East Rana.
There is no permanent presence of any of our staff in Libya, which is not yet necessary.
Is there any Russian military advisors, instructors in Libya now?
And if so, on whose side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All the talk and publications about this are not true.
But in your contact group, the ex-military include...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
Like when we go to hot spots.
Or cities that have been closed to a certain point for us, such as Misurata (where the militias that have played a role in the overthrow of the Libyan leader, Muammar Gaddafi, in 2011 and have been significantly intensified in the years to come.
