And two weeks ago, there was the first shipment of Libyan oil to Rosneft.
What will Russia do with it?
I'm guessing to resell.
What other economic interests do Russia have in Libya?
Plans to re-sign the contracts under Muammar Gaddafi.
These include previous transport agreements (railway construction), energy (electrification) and a number of others.
Do the Libyans have anything to pay for?
Well, they have oil.
So this is, as in the case of Iran, the oil-for-service scheme?
I don't know what the pattern will be, I don't deal with these very things.
In fact, the economy for Russia in Libya is not the main thing.
We're actually doing peacekeeping work there.
The main thing for us is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans to negotiate with one another so that they can establish order, and Libya has ceased to be a propitious environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, the main task is to help the Libyan people and to get the terrorists out of there.
Do you have any data on the presence in Libya (now or before) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that, to date, no one from Russia or from other countries of the former USSR has been there.
He said he's got about 50,000 phone records from Islamist and radical groups (in Libya - OS) and there's no Russian talk.
