Carter was found guilty in June of the manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on 13 July 2014.
Roe's father said at the Thursday hearing, "My family has been saddened.
My son was my best friend."
Carter was allowed to stay free until the appeal.
She was facing a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her lawyers said that both she and Roy had mental health problems.
Carter, dressed in red trousers and a cream blouse, listened to the sentence standing up, shrugging her hands and lowering her eyes.
"In her actions, she killed Conrad Roy," the prosecutor told the court.
"She cut off his life to improve hers.
She didn't accept responsibility," she said.
"She didn't show any remorse."
But Carter's lawyer said it was "a tragic incident that she deeply regrets."
But Judge Lawrence Monice said that in his view, her "age, maturity, or even mental illness didn't have an appreciable effect on her actions."
The Prosecutor read out the statements of Roy Lynn Roy's mother, which said, "it's not a day since I didn't mourn the loss of my dear son.
I want him to be proud of me and the way I'm doing it - I'm trying to support his sisters, despite all the pain that will stay with us forever," he says.
Roy's sister, Kamdin Roy, said that she was incessantly persecuted by the idea that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become an aunt of his children.
"Like a man who's always been with me since I was born, it's a pain that will stay with me for the rest of my life," she said.
This case is likely to be a legal precedent, as there is no law in Massachusetts that would make it a liability to counsel a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in the car with symptoms of CO2 poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The incident drew the country's attention when it was reported that he was forced to kill Carter's message.
"You can hang yourself, jump off the roof, stab yourself with a knife, I don't know how many ways," she wrote in a number of messages sent two weeks before his death, when he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before suicidal, she wrote, "You have to do it, Conrad" and "You just have to turn on the ignition, and you'll be free and happy."
Judge Monice said Carter wanted to get attention by means of Roy's death, and he barred her from talking to the press to keep her from getting what she wanted.
