Russian vice-premier Mutko: "We will meet the requirements of the VADA Road Map in the near future."
Russian vice-premier Vitaly Mutko said that the conditions of the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) for the resumption of the work of the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (RUSADA) would be met in the near future.
“A stage in the implementation of the requirements has been completed, and RUSADA has been given the right to plan and run the tests in conjunction with the UKAD (Anti-Doping Agency of the United Kingdom).
The BADA Road Map was updated accordingly,” Mutko said on Thursday.
The Prime Minister commented on the second part of the Road Map of WADA to reinstate compliance with the Code, which lists the conditions for the resumption of the work of RUSADA and has recently been published on the organization ' s website.
According to Mutko, it does not contain anything that would present a problem for Russia.
"Everything has been announced, everything will be done.
And the results will be presented to the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and the WADA in the near future,” he added.
But one of the requirements on the list is that the Russian anti-diping structures should publicly accept the results of the VADA-ordered investigation of Canadian jurist Richard McLaren, who claimed that doping in Russian sports was controlled by the state.
On this subject, Mutko said, "We are investigating, as our anti-doping system has failed.
All measures have been taken.
But there have been no government programs, and we will not accept what has not happened."
Mutko echoed the words of William Smirnov, head of the Russian independent public anti-doping commission.
On the morning of the same day, in an interview with the Russian edition of the Rsport, Smirnov acknowledged the previous problems in the Russian anti-doping structures, but added: "We have repeatedly said that the report contains certain controversial positions and provisions.
No one is going to take this report, without a doubt,' Smirnov added.
WADA removed RUSAD from doping control in November 2015 after a doping scandal.
In June this year, however, he was allowed to plan and coordinate the test under the supervision of international experts and the British Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD).
After a visit to the Moscow office of the organization in July, Olivier Niggley, Director-General of WADA, stated that RUSADA was “moving in the right direction” to re-establish its work.
