Starts that will help your company not become another Uber
Aimee Errett wanted to assess the level of satisfaction among his startup staff in the area of electronic commerce, but the polls didn't work.
The answers were often vague, pointless, or, worse, untrue.
And even though she promised anonymity, some staff didn't trust the process.
“He has never been consistent and objective,” said Errett, the manager of a 75-person company in San Francisco, “Madison Reed, an e-commerce company in the area of hair care.
She therefore sought assistance from third parties.
A new type of start-up in the area of staff is now emerging, helping companies to find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licenseing software, which is designed to measure the involvement of staff members, they enable companies to make prompt inquiries, to refer to certain teams and population groups, to offer staff anonymity and a hotline for complaints, and, in some cases, to allow whistle-blowers to pass down the top management and to address the directorate directly.
"Now we have such tools as Strava and Fitbit to monitor health, and where is Fitbit for your company? ", says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of the Glint startup in Redwood City, whose analytical programs are used by companies to measure employee involvement.
Errett told us that she has gained a better understanding of what her staff think and feel in three years of Glint use.
In addition to the express polls and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers a company's thermal map and illustrates which units have more complaints and which managers have a low rating of approval, so that it can understand why.
The companies are a bit aware of the need to control the workplace, or they will become the next Uber, who was involved in the scandal when a former employee posted a blog that described the aggressive environment in which those who expressed dissatisfaction were punished.
For start-ups like "Glint", this desire to control the situation is an opportunity for profit-making business.
The “Let's Talk About Pay” Internet Portal, dedicated to financial technology, estimates that the global governance, regulation, and alignment industry can cost over $118.7 billion by 2020.
The "Convercent" start from Denver, Colorado, helping companies to prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a small increase in interest and activity earlier this year against the background of the fall in Uber's reputation.
Convercent has almost 600 clients, including Airbnb, Microsoft, and Tesla.
Uber has recently emerged as a client.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customized interviews of the staff's views, to collect confidential responses in real time, and to view thermal maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages, which allows staff to report bad behaviour.
And if the top manager is involved, the complaints go straight to the office.
“The court of public opinion has overtaken the powers of the inspectors,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If it turns out that the company is not treating the staff or acting unethically, even if the inspector does not intervene, the company may face costly consequences in the form of client boycotts, staff outflows, and lawsuits, Queenlan reported.
Ruby Tuesday, a network of restaurants with more than 25,000 employees in 500 establishments, has used Convercent for over a year to make sure that the staff are aware of the rules and procedures, and to suggest a simple way to contact the company's head office.
In the past, if the staff member wanted to report a problem, he or she had to look for a phone number or a head office e-mail, file an official complaint, and hope that it would be taken seriously.
This was often a frightening and awkward experience, reported James Vitrano, the head of the legal office of Ruby Tuesday, who said that there was no normal way to follow up on the staff's complaints.
Now, when the company is using Convercent, the problems that used to be hidden from office managers in other cities or states – such as discrimination, charisma, and unfair pay – can be detected and addressed more quickly.
“I can get closer to a complete, comprehensive understanding of the situation of the staff,” said Vitrano, who runs the Risk Management Team of Ruby Tuesday.
“And we are protecting our shareholders from legal proceedings with the staff.”
According to Queenland, companies began to take the ethics, values, and involvement of employees more seriously in 2002, after Arthur Andersen’s accounting firm collapsed on account of ethical irregularities as a result of the Dela Enron.
But it was only when “social networks have become massively common,” that the companies realized that they would not be able to keep their dirty underwear from viral distribution on the net.
“Before starting to use technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both "Glint" and "Conversent" offer their software as a service, charging companies regularly for the use of their products.
It's a business model and an opportunity that won the approval of venture investors who supported both startups.
In February, "Conversent" received $10 million in funding from firms such as "Sapphire Ventures" and "Tola Capital", bringing the company's total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the company's total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly astonishing given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
The growing volume of research has shown that today's employees expect more from their jobs than they used to do.
In markets with strong competition, such as the Silicon Valley, high wages, and interesting projects, they are just the necessary minimum.
The employees want to feel that they are accepted and appreciated, and that they are devoting their time to a company with a positive mission.
“When people are happy to work in a company, feel that they are being heard, and that the work they do is a result, they're trying to make such a company a success,” says Nina McQueen, the vice-president for global benefits and satisfaction at LinkedIn, where both Convercent and Glint are used.
Investors receive income when business from their portfolio goes well; business from companies goes well when employees are loyal and involved.
If third-party analytical tools promise to increase the commitment and involvement of staff, it is not surprising that they find support.
In the workplace, culture experts argue that it is important to have data on the involvement of staff.
But the data is useless until the company's trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks for feedback, it can give the impression that a change is coming.
And if changes don't come fast enough, or if they don't come at all, there can be frustration, and the staff lose interest.
“If you're going to ask for 4,000 offers, you have to be ready to hold 4,000 interviews,” says Russell Rut, president of the management firm of Kotter International, who had to see companies make a mistake, relying too much on data collection.
"Because if you don't go to the end, the staff will wonder, "Do you really hear me?
Do you care?
And if you don't care, why don't I care?"
According to Errett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly staff interviews, is in a position to take action on the same day that someone reports the problem with the help of Glint.
And after gathering feedback from the staff, dissatisfied with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize a number of teams within the company and introduce a communication training to address the problem.
Ruby Tuesday is learning new things about its employees and hopes that in the long run it will be able to more effectively retain its staff in an industry known for high turnover.
"If you don't try to create a culture of transparency, you'll lose people," Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose clients.
And if you lose your clients, you lose your company.
