Create a novel-comic: One lock in English history
In the recent past, Scotty's small castle was filmed in a music video called "Squeeze", and in the 1970s and 1980s served as a shelter for Margaret Thatcher.
But 700 years from his cozy spot in the Bule Valley in Kent County, he was watching a turbulent history around, and now he inspired Jamie Rhoades, a yorkshire with a filthy hair and a tendency to have a history, to a Roman-comics.
"I think it's so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago," he says.
"You feel it in person when you hold this letter in your hand."
"The Castle in England" ranges from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era and speaks of families who lived in Scotty; each story is illustrated by a young British artist, Isaac Lenkevich, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer, and Isabel Greenberg.
This is not the first book of Rhoades, which is based on archival data: in 2014, he wrote "The Tooths of a Dead Man and Other Stories", a collection of British Library records; this project suddenly touched him to the depths of his heart.
"I could have just been touched by a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for the Jacobites," he says.
"This is his fingerprint."
And the emails always smell like smoke, because in those days the light was lighted up.
And in 300 years, in the future, you think you're there too.
Ah, I love the archives!"
For a man who has such a passion for old papers, to receive support from the National Foundation and the English Arts Council, and to live in a castle for four months ("I've been a bit there") seems too good to be true.
Rhoades spent all day studying the "new" Victorian lock, walking through the archives, and looking at a lot of property treasures and antique things -- like the head of hyena on the walls or the bottles of centuries in the shatter.
He was walking through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talking to the foresters, the gardeners, and sometimes the artists who worked on the illustrations to his book.
Then at night, he "dranks whiskey and sits down to write."
The history of the Castle of Scotty is not very well known, because the National Foundation was not able to gain full access to it until 2006, when the last heir, Elizabeth Hassy, died.
When Rhoades arrived ten years later, the staff was just beginning to deal with the archive, which he described as "what the aristocrats have been down in the attic for centuries."
The journals, the British Empire e-mails, the charts showing who owned what you think land disputes are boring, Rhoades says, but two families have been fighting for this berth.
You know, it's like that, guys!"
In some of the history of the compilation, the lock is becoming a starting point for the wider search in English history: for example, in "The Workman", the hero is leaving the newly built lock to join the Christian Revolution of 1381.
"There is evidence of a mutiny that took place in the castle in 1380, in a book called "The knightly families of Kent and Sussex," Rhoades says.
"The Crusade Revolt began in these places, and I thought the revolt was a good start.
Maybe they were bound."
Other narratives are closely related to the history of the castle, such as the Priest, which speaks of the Jesuit priest, whom the Darryl family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "Smuggling" about an 18th-century smuggler, Arthur Darryl, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by filling a coffin with stones (this was found a few years later when the coffin was dug up).
The Darrells are the favorite family of Rhoades who lived in Scotty: "The Gentlemans seem to have been a complete scam, always in debt, and spend money on things they couldn't afford.
In different generations, Darryl men have been able to solve their debt problems by marrying rich old women -- I imagine them as a company of pretty guys who know how to take care of the heirs of big fortunes."
After completing his work at Castle Rhoades, he's looking for other ways to get a unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in the countryside, where he wrote a graphical novel about Elimenmeki, a place where there was a sanatorium at the beginning of the 20th century, and then it fell back into the woods.
But Scotty is still a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave," he said.
"I felt like, damn it, I have to go back to my real life."
