Red meat, dairy and chocolate can help lighten the VOC.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent studies suggest the opposite: a diet rich in meat squirrels and dairy products can help to alleviate the symptoms of inflammable intestinal diseases.
It is an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, leading to colicing and excrement, chronic or bloody diarrhea, loss of weight, and extreme fatigue.
Normally, to alleviate the symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy, but researchers at Washington University have found that the main amino acid of triptophan protein contributes to the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
The lead researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that the intestines in the intestines are making sure that the harmful germs that come with food do not penetrate the body.
Cells that can start an inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance by protecting the body without harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is overstated in the direction of inflammation, it can lead to inflammable intestinal diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice with a certain bacterium in their intestines have an increasing cell tolerance.
And this bacteria needs a triptophan, one of the building elements of a squirrel, to start the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said, "We have established a link between one type of bacteria, the Lactobacillas reuteri, which is part of the normal intestinal microbiomy, and the evolution of the cell population that increases tolerance.
The more the triptophane was in the mice's diet, the more these immune cells they had."
He suggested that the same would work for people: a combination of L. reuteri and a rich triptophan diet can contribute to a more tolerant and less prone to inflammation in the intestines.
Postdock, Dr. Louise Cervantes-Barraganwas, in a study of a type of tolerance-enhancing immunocells, found that one group of test mice had these cells, and the other group, which belonged to the same line but was kept separate, had none.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by mice's intestinal germs, by the communities of bacteria, viruses, and fungi, which usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the intestine cells has been sequented, and six species of bacteria have been found in mice with immune cells but not in mice without them.
Mouses grown in a sterile environment that didn't have a good microbiomy and didn't develop this kind of immune cell have L. reuteri, and they have immunized cells.
To understand the effect of bacteria on the immune system, the researchers raised L. reuteri in a liquid environment, and then moved a small portion of the liquid, without the bacteria, to the non-deficient immune cells separated from mice.
Immune cells have become more tolerance-enhancing cells.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it was a by-product of triptophane treatment, known as indol-3-milk acid.
When the researchers doubled the number of triptophane in mice's food, the number of these cells rose by about 50 per cent, but when the triptophane level was halved, the number of cells also fell by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that humans have the same tolerant cell as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in their gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether by-products of the L. reuteri have contributed to the development of cells in humans as in mice, but people with inflammable intestinal diseases have been found to be deficient in the genes associated with the trictopane.
She says, "Perhaps we need to step up the development of these cells, because these cells are dependent on inflammatory processes on the inside of the intestines.
High levels of triptopane, with L. reuteri, can potentially result in an expansion of their population. "
