The White House Requisition cost the taxpayers thousands of dollars.
According to the records of the armed forces given to the magazine Time, the White House's decision last month to bring a Marine Helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American industrial production cost the taxpayers a total of $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as "Marine One", when the president is on board, has become a central feature of a White House event on 17 July, at which American construction programmes were shown.
President Donald Trump, Vice-President Mike Pence, and White House top officials have been looking at the tech products from all 50 states.
The helicopter in Connecticut was positioned next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a freighter from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Marine Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the Division for Helicopter Management, the White House Military Department ordered the presence of the Helicopter in a private order, or “FRAGO”, just 36 hours before the Helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of an “unusual” event.
“I just wanted you to know that you know, because this is an unusually well-known press event,” wrote the commander of HMX-1 in an e-mail to his head, the first deputy airmaster of the Marine Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive in the South Lawn at about 7 a.m. on 17 July to attend an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and would stay there until the lawn was freed between 6 p.m. and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be needed to return in accordance with the time limit.
The first crew was escorting a helicopter during the event, and the unit's security officers remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It was not clear from the records received by the Time Journal whether a second crew was needed at the end of the day.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using State property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 specified whether the activity was in conflict with the order.
“We asked, among other things, if it was a violation of Hatch's law, and we were told no,” the commander wrote.
“You don't seem to have a place to go,” the Deputy Chief replied.
The event "Done in America" was declared an official event by the White House, and it was not subject to the Hatch Act.
But even formal events have political notes.
During the event, the President made an effort to advance the reform of health, which was at the time in the Senate, and lauded the attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft, known as Marine One and Air Force One for political purposes, is hardly new.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But it's unusual to ask for them alone in the interest of photography.
Trump was already the subject of a discussion in February, when the presidential plane passed in the background during his first election meeting in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was full of complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessor.
“The White House is fascinated by the "made in America" show, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American material,” said Lyndsey Walters, the White House Press Secretary.
HMX-1 crews often fly around the Washington Agglomeration and on the South Lawn to train the President of the United States to transport to the White House to an inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 carried out 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight for the "Done in the Americas" event was counted as part of a month's training.
The unit ' s rotary-wing aircraft also overflyed 11 additional hours on that day as part of the “non-presidential support tasks”.
According to the White House, the taxpayers did not spend on any of the other items presented at the event.
A representative of Sikorsky reported that the company was not part of the South Lawn Helicopter Demonstration.
HMX-1 does not account for the budget for the presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to Department of Defense time-rates for the fiscal year 2017, the VH-3D rate of reimbursement is US$24,380 per flight hour.
The unit records that air time in air was 30 minutes each way from its airstrip at the Quantico Marine Airbase in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using a helicopter is much lower than this rate.
“Telling the cost to the taxpayers on the basis of an estimated rate of reimbursement is very wrong,” says Walters.
“These indicative rates include personnel, maintenance and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual allocation”.
According to a study carried out in 2015 by the RAND Corporation, the rates of reimbursement do not include the cost of the personnel, but do take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and the costs specified in the contract.
At the time, the former White House Spicer Spokesman spoke out to defend the use of a helicopter for the event.
"The idea is to show this week things done in America," Spicer said.
"And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they are contributing to national security, and that there are, I guess, hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose job is dependent on it.
And I think, like most Americans, we're all proud of this chopper and other military equipment, which so many Americans have been working so hard on.
Therefore, of course, it is entirely appropriate to take note of this.
It was not clear if Trump interacted with a helicopter by looking at the South Lawn during the event, but he was exactly in the driver's seat in a fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump approached Sikorsky for a joke with the press on the company's own fleet of products.
"I know very well "Sikorsky," the president said. "I have three."
